{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"72dff9fd-6053-4527-863b-c33351730b75","content":"Yes, your tutorial's approach is correct and these APIs remain valid in .NET 10 MAUI.\n\n**`ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`** — Correct. Add the iOS platform-specific namespace and apply it to your `ContentPage`:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\">\n```\n\nThis keeps content clear of the notch, status bar, and home indicator.\n\n**`IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"`** — Also correct. Apply it to a layout (like `Grid`) so it extends edge-to-edge behind the safe area, which is exactly what you want for a full-bleed background image:\n\n```xml\n<Grid IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\">\n    <Image Source=\"background.png\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n</Grid>\n```\n\n**Typical pattern combining both:**\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"...\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\">\n    <Grid>\n        <!-- Background extends behind notch -->\n        <Grid IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\">\n            <Image Source=\"bg.png\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n        </Grid>\n        <!-- Content respects safe area -->\n        <VerticalStackLayout Padding=\"20\">\n            <Label Text=\"Hello, world!\" />\n        </VerticalStackLayout>\n    </Grid>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nThe page-level `UseSafeArea` insets your content, while `IgnoreSafeArea` on the background grid overrides that for just that element. This is the standard approach.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"60ef0f53-cb83-4d63-a369-0c3cc48411a2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI safe area handling on iOS, specifically about two properties:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` - a platform-specific property for ContentPage\n2. `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` - a property on Grid\n\nLet me think about what I know about .NET MAUI safe area APIs and whether they've changed in .NET 10.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the iOS safe area handling has evolved:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` - This was the original platform-specific API from Xamarin.Forms that carried over to early .NET MAUI. \n\nThe `UseSafeArea` property lives in the `Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific` namespace and controls whether a page respects iOS safe area insets. Meanwhile, `IgnoreSafeArea` is a layout property that lets views extend beyond the safe area boundaries to the screen edges. I should check what's changed in .NET 10 regarding these APIs. The `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` property respects notches and home indicators on iOS, while `IgnoreSafeArea` on layout views lets specific content extend beyond those boundaries—useful for full-bleed backgrounds that should ignore the safe area constraints. Both approaches work in .NET 10 MAUI—the `UseSafeArea` attribute with the iOS namespace handles notches and status bars, while `IgnoreSafeArea` lets individual layouts extend behind those areas when needed, like for full-screen backgrounds. This is a straightforward answer based on established MAUI APIs.","outputTokens":1484,"requestId":"B808:1EC425:1B4966:236340:69FFDBB1"},"id":"95fd8315-3292-4156-b7a0-2e4f1162b1e6","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:13:50.928Z","parentId":"396c6538-218d-4e52-9005-04bc18d00d49"}
